The first issue of the new student newspaper, the Minerva Column, is released on April 13, 2025. The issue features 10 pieces, all written by members of the M27 cohort. From the latest on the cultural trends in Seoul to insights into the consequences of the January LA wildfires to the status of AI use at the university, the paper brings student perspectives on topics from both within and outside the Minerva bubble.

The new newspaper team hopes to add value to both contributors and readers. In an interview, the Column co-founder, Camila López González (M27), emphasises the importance of creating a shared space for important conversations.

"I wish we had this while the USCIS crisis still was going on," she says, referring to the F-1 visa crisis of fall 2024 where the United States Immigration and Citizenship Services (USCIS) issued a [policy clarification](https://washdiplomat.com/a-little-noticed-change-in-us-visa-policy-threatens-global-education/) about how long international students in the U.S. could maintain their status while studying abroad — changing the guidance from "indefinitely" to "max 5 months" and shaking much of the foundation of Minerva University's global rotation model. The guidance was later revoked, allowing Minerva to resume its usual operations, but the issue caused much stress to both students and faculty. Camila explains that she thinks a university paper could have provided much-needed space for shared discussion in that challenging time.

## A Growing Team

The small team has been working from the 20th floor of the Sinseol residence hall building in Seoul, in what they have come to call simply the "news room." Here, they have developed editorial guidelines, pitched ideas, and discussed source quality and marketing strategies.

![The team at work in the news room]()

The group started out by inviting the whole cohort to a meeting to set intentions and discuss the purpose and plan for the paper. "Thankfully, some really enthusiastic and talented people showed up!" Camila says.

The next time they met, fellow M27 Elfriede Suarez Reichenberger shared her experience from *The New York Times* and gave everyone an introduction to journalistic writing. According to the team, that foundation was essential in setting the tone and inspiring their writing. Camila emphasises that an important value for the group is to be "assignment resilient." "That means we want to create space for meaningful conversations even when people are knee-deep in writing code or finishing up their LBAs!"

"I enjoy working with this team so much, but we always want to invite new contributors — writers, editors, or someone with a passion for drawing comics — anything really!" Camila concludes.

## Editorial Independence, but Institutional Support

While the Minerva Column is an independent effort for and by Minerva students, it has received encouragement from professors and ASM funding for empanadas at the launch party.

At the same time, the team is committed to maintaining editorial independence and fostering critical discussions, even — or maybe especially — on topics that may cause controversy within the institution.

Daniya Ishankulova (M27), a journalist and founding member of the Minerva Column, puts it plainly: "We need a space for cohort and university-level discussions about local and global issues, with more thought-through pieces than what you see in the different Telegram chats!"

## Future Plans

The group is not planning to do full issues regularly, but hopes to keep publishing pieces continuously on the website. "In the future, we might make issues retroactive," Daniya explains. Articles will be published as they are completed, with full issues compiled and sent out at regular intervals. "But don't worry, we'll make sure there are some new, never-seen-before treats in each complete publication!" she assures us.
